  <body>
    <div rend="parallel">
      <lg xml:id="MTA55">
<l>avaṉṟama revviṉaiya rākilu meṅkō</l>
<l>ṉavaṉṟamarē yeṉṟoḻiva tallā – ṉamaṉṟamarā</l>
<l>lārāyap paṭṭaṟiyār kaṇṭī raravaṇaimēṟ</l>
<l>pērāyaṟ kāṭpaṭṭār pēr</l>
      </lg>
      <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>‘His people, whatever [their] karma, are our king’s people,’</l>
<l>apart from being left with that thought, they do not know</l>
<l>of being examined<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">The basis of ārāya paṭṭu aṟiyār is an idiomatic formation of an absolutive followed by a negative form of aṟital, “to know”, literally “not knowing of doing something”, that is, never doing it, in this case with a passive component “they are never being examined”.</note> by Yama’s people<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">The expression namaṉ tamar, “Yama’s people”, refers to the helpmates of the god of death who brings in humans for karmic reckoning, a procedure from which the devotees of the lord will be exempt.</note>, see, those named</l>
<l>servants<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">Or: “or those named after the servants.”</note> of the great cowherd on the serpent bed.</l>
      </lg>
    </div>
  </body>
</text>
